findings.message:
This is three files' worth of pattern for what is, in reality, a lookup table. An abstract base class, two strategy subclasses, and a factory — all to dispatch on six hard-coded strings. The PR description justifies it with 'so we can add more coupon types later,' but YAGNI: when 'date-bound, customer-specific' coupons actually arrive they will need a database, not a deeper class hierarchy. Replace all of this with a plain `Record` and one function:
```ts
const COUPONS: Record<string, { kind: 'percent' | 'flat'; value: number }> = {
  WELCOME10: { kind: 'percent', value: 0.10 },
  FIVEOFF:   { kind: 'flat',    value: 500  },
  // ...
};
export function applyCoupon(amount: number, code: string): number {
  const coupon = COUPONS[code];
  if (!coupon) return amount;
  return coupon.kind === 'percent'
    ? Math.floor(amount * (1 - coupon.value))
    : Math.max(0, amount - coupon.value);
}
```
Three classes, one factory, and an inheritance tree deleted. When the rules actually get complex you'll know exactly what shape they need to take.
